{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525113","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525113"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:12:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:12:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14056"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14056"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.24,0.05,0.4,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6710"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92637"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6710"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14056"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75979"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"2787"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11624"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13945"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31235"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31236"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31755"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43930"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92637","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92637"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of nausea, vomiting, and increasing drowsiness. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His partner reports that he does not consume alcohol or recreational drugs. On examination, he appears unwell with a pulse rate of 120/min, blood pressure 105/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. He sleeps throughout the review and rouses with difficulty. He does not respond at all to voice and opens his eyes only briefly after painful stimuli, after which there is abnormal flexion of his limbs. He makes incomprehensible noises only, and does not follow any commands. His abdomen is soft with mild right upper quadrant tenderness. He is jaundiced, but otherwise has no stigmata of chronic liver disease. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBilirubin: 85 \u00b5mol/L (5-21)\u003Cbr /\u003EALT: 2500 U/L (7-56)\u003Cbr /\u003EAST: 2800 U/L (10-40)\u003Cbr /\u003EINR: 3.8 (0.8-1.2)\u003Cbr /\u003ECreatinine: 110 \u00b5mol/L (45-90)\u003Cbr /\u003EAmmonia: 80 \u00b5mol/L (11-32)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral lactulose","Rectal lactulose","Fresh frozen plasma","Intubation","Transfer to a liver transplant centre"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of acute liver failure (ALF) and hepatic encephalopathy. ALF is characterized by the rapid onset of severe hepatic dysfunction in a patient without pre-existing liver disease. Key features include coagulopathy (INR \u0026gt;1.5), hepatic encephalopathy, and often jaundice, all of which are present in this case. The most appropriate next step in management is \u003Cstrong\u003Eintubation\u003C/strong\u003E. Given the patient\u0027s decreasing level of consciousness (consistent with grade 3-4 encephalopathy and a GCS of 7-8) and the risk of aspiration, securing the airway is crucial. Intubation also allows for better control of oxygenation and ventilation, which is important in managing potential cerebral oedema associated with ALF.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral lactulose\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Erectal lactulose\u003C/strong\u003E are not recommended in acute liver failure. While lactulose is commonly used to treat hepatic encephalopathy in chronic liver disease, it is not beneficial in acute liver failure and can, in fact, cause problematic bowel distension. The management of hepatic encephalopathy in ALF focuses on treating the underlying cause of liver failure, providing supportive care, and potentially liver transplantation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransfer to a liver transplant centre\u003C/strong\u003E is an important step in the management of ALF, but it is not the most immediate priority. Before transfer, the patient\u0027s airway needs to be secured and their condition stabilized. Once the patient is intubated and initial management has begun, discussion with a liver transplant centre should be the next priority.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering fresh frozen plasma\u003C/strong\u003E to correct the coagulopathy is not routinely recommended in ALF unless there is active bleeding or an invasive procedure is planned. Prophylactic correction of INR does not improve outcomes and may mask the progression of liver failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter intubation, the patient should receive close monitoring in an ICU setting. This includes frequent neurological assessments, intracranial pressure monitoring if severe encephalopathy develops, and management of complications such as hypoglycemia, electrolyte imbalances, and renal failure. Prophylactic antibiotics are usually given in cases of severe encephalopathy due to the high risk of infection. Efforts should be made to identify and treat the underlying cause of ALF, which may include viral hepatitis, drug-induced liver injury, or autoimmune hepatitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEarly consultation with a liver transplant center is crucial, as liver transplantation may be life-saving in cases of ALF that fail to improve with medical management. Prognostic scoring systems such as the King\u0027s College Criteria can help identify patients who are likely to require transplantation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute liver failure is characterised by coagulopathy and encephalopathy in the absence of known liver disease.","Lactulose is not recommended to manage encephalopathy in acute liver failure.","Early involvement of intensive care and a liver transplant centre is crucial in managing acute liver failure."],"references":["European Association for the Study of the Liver. (2017). EASL Clinical Practical Guidelines on the management of acute (fulminant) liver failure. Journal of hepatology, 66(5), 1047\u20131081."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75979"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14056"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75979","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75979"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-18T18:07:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-18T18:10:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6710"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92637"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self